                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=211">Susan Estrich</a></strong></p>
                <p>An op-ed by Prof. Susan Estrich ran about the difference between primary and general elections.</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
        <li class="clearfix" style="padding-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 1px #e3e3e3 solid;">
        
            <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=236"><img src="/portal/directory/photos100x100/Matsusaka_John.jpg" width="100" height="100" alt="John Matsusaka" class="fleft" /></a>
        
            <div class="descr">
                <h2><a href="http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/general-news/20100523/electing-judges-a-lottery-of-name-gender-and-occupation" target="_blank" style="text-decoration: none;">Pasadena Star-News</a></h2>
                <h3>May 22, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=236">John Matsusaka</a></strong></p>
                <p>John Matsusaka of USC's Initiative and Referendum Institute was interviewed about California's hybrid election and gubernatorial appointment system for Superior Court judges.</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
        <li class="clearfix" style="padding-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 1px #e3e3e3 solid;">
        
            <img src="/portal/directory/photos100x100/USCLawLogo.gif" width="100" height="100" alt="USC Gould School of Law" class="fleft" />
        
            <div class="descr">
                <h2><a href="http://www.laweekly.com/2010-05-20/la-life/elyn-saks-a-matter-of-degrees" target="_blank" style="text-decoration: none;">LA Weekly</a></h2>
                <h3>May 21, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=300">Elyn Saks</a></strong></p>
                <p>L.A. Weekly featured Elyn Saks of the USC Gould School in its 2010 People issue. The story highlighted Saks' book "The Center Cannot Hold: My Journey Through Madness," about her struggles with schizophrenia. "My goals were to put a human face on schizophrenia and dispel some myths that were very destructive," Saks said.</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
        <li class="clearfix" style="padding-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 1px #e3e3e3 solid;">
        
            <img src="/portal/directory/photos100x100/USCLawLogo.gif" width="100" height="100" alt="USC Gould School of Law" class="fleft" />
        
            <div class="descr">
                <h2><a href="http://www.independent.com/events/2010/may/21/15617/" target="_blank" style="text-decoration: none;">Santa Barbara Independent</a></h2>
                <h3>May 21, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=300">Elyn Saks</a></strong></p>
                <p>Santa Barbara Independent reported that Elyn Saks of the USC Gould School will receive a Heroes of Hope award from the Mental Health Association in Santa Barbara County.</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
        <li class="clearfix" style="padding-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 1px #e3e3e3 solid;">
        
            <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=220"><img src="/portal/directory/photos100x100/Hadfield_G2010.jpg" width="100" height="100" alt="Gillian Hadfield" class="fleft" /></a>
        
            <div class="descr">
                <h2 style="color: #000000;">AM Law Daily</h2>
                <h3>May 19, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=220">Gillian Hadfield</a></strong></p>
                <p>USCs Southern California Innovation Projects workshop, Building Better Lawyers, was featured. Co-organized by Prof. Gillian Hadfield, the event was held at the Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences at Stanford University. It was an all-star crew of general counsel, academics, and law firm leaders, and we heard about a number of initiatives from law firms (e.g., DLAPiper and Howrey both implementing programs to better assess and train associates), law schools (e.g., Stanford, Northwestern, and Indiana all trying to make legal training more experiential and client-oriented), and clients (e.g., HP has hired five grads straight from elite law schools and is developing a focused on-boarding curriculum), the story reported.</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
        <li class="clearfix" style="padding-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 1px #e3e3e3 solid;">
        
            <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=219"><img src="/portal/directory/photos100x100/Gross_A.jpg" width="100" height="100" alt="Ariela Gross" class="fleft" /></a>
        
            <div class="descr">
                <h2 style="color: #000000;">Los Angeles Daily Journal</h2>
                <h3>May 18, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=219">Ariela Gross</a></strong></p>
                <p>An op-ed by Prof. Ariela Gross was published about reparations for slavery. Harvard University scholar Henry Louis Gates Jr. argues that because American plantation owners share the blame for slavery with African slavers, African Americans should put aside reparations claims against the U.S. government and institutions that profited from slavery, Gross wrote. I believe this argument is ill-founded. African Americans claims against their own government and domestic institutions are not diminished even by proof positive that African traders understood the horrors to which they were dispatching fellow Africans. Efforts to call the U.S. government to account for the legally sanctioned and supported enslavement of millions of human beings rest on the history of slavery and its aftermath right here on U.S. shores. Her piece also ran on the American Constitution Society website.
</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
        <li class="clearfix" style="padding-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 1px #e3e3e3 solid;">
        
            <img src="/portal/directory/photos100x100/USCLawLogo.gif" width="100" height="100" alt="USC Gould School of Law" class="fleft" />
        
            <div class="descr">
                <h2 style="color: #000000;">Los Angeles Business Journal</h2>
                <h3>May 18, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: USC Gould School of Law</strong></p>
                <p>A story featured winners of the New Venture Seed Competition sponsored by the USC Marshall School's Lloyd Greif Center for Entrepreneurial Studies. USC Gould School student Paul Del Piero won the top prize in the graduate-level competition for his proposal to create ConservatorshipHelp.com, a Web site that would help create legal documents for conservatorships and adult guardianships. </p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
        <li class="clearfix" style="padding-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 1px #e3e3e3 solid;">
        
            <img src="/portal/directory/photos100x100/USCLawLogo.gif" width="100" height="100" alt="USC Gould School of Law" class="fleft" />
        
            <div class="descr">
                <h2 style="color: #000000;">CNBC</h2>
                <h3>May 18, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: USC Gould School of Law</strong></p>
                <p>A story included the 2007 USC Gould School commencement speech by Berkshire Hathaway Vice President Charles Munger on a list of the 10 Best Graduation Speeches of All Time. You want to deliver to the world what you would buy if you were on the other end, Munger told graduates. </p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
        <li class="clearfix" style="padding-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 1px #e3e3e3 solid;">
        
            <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=211"><img src="/portal/directory/photos100x100/sestrich.jpg" width="100" height="100" alt="Susan Estrich" class="fleft" /></a>
        
