                <h2 style="color: #000000;">Pasadena Star-News</h2>
                <h3>May 11, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=227">Daniel Klerman</a></strong></p>
                <p>Prof. Daniel Klerman was interviewed about President Obamas nomination of Solicitor General Elena Kagan for the U.S. Supreme Court. Klerman said he doesn't consider Kagans lack of judicial experience a problem. In fact, he said, it's useful to have judges with a range of experiences.  Having someone who has served as Solicitor General, as dean of a law school and who has advised U.S. Presidents as Kagan has is "extremely useful experience for a Supreme Court nominee, and she'll learn all she needs to about judging in a year or two," he said.</p>
