            <div class="descr">
                <h2 style="color: #000000;">Los Angeles Daily Journal</h2>
                <h3>May 10, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=226">Gregory Keating</a></strong></p>
                <p>Prof. Gregory Keating was interviewed about whether it is a conflict to represent different kinds of plaintiffs in similar cases. While such jousting appears to be motivated by power and fees, "there could be an underlying basis" for conflict of interest concerns, said Keating. The two different types of claims might proceed on different theories of liability - breach of warranty for economic loss and defective condition for personal injury, which could result in differing theories of liability and damages, Keating said. 
</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
