            <div class="descr">
                <h2><a href="http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2010/apr/30/video-spotlights-legislation-on-birthright/" target="_blank" style="text-decoration: none;">The Christian Science Monitor</a></h2>
                <h3>April 30, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=214">Niels W. Frenzen</a></strong></p>
                <p>Prof. Niels Frenzen was quoted about a movement to amend the Immigration and Nationality Act to limit automatic citizenship for children born in the United States. Frenzen, director of the Immigration Law Clinic at the University of Southern California, called the idea a non-starter because it runs afoul of the 14th Amendment. Can it be done under the Constitution as it is currently written? Of course not. Thats crazy, Frenzen said. Could the Constitution in theory be amended to change the way we confer citizenship? Theoretically, yes; in reality, no. Is it a good idea? No.</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
