        <li class="clearfix" style="padding-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 1px #e3e3e3 solid;">
        
            <img src="/portal/directory/photos100x100/USCLawLogo.gif" width="100" height="100" alt="USC Gould School of Law" class="fleft" />
        
            <div class="descr">
                <h2><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/11/opinion/11stevens.html " target="_blank" style="text-decoration: none;">New York Times</a></h2>
                <h3>April 11, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: USC Gould School of Law</strong></p>
                <p>Prof. Susan Estrich wrote an opinion piece about retiring U.S. Supreme Court Justice John Paul Stevens. Estrich recalled serving as a clerk for Stevens in the 1970s. "The petition came in around 9 p.m. on May 24, 1979. A man named John Spenkelink, convicted in the murder of a fellow hitchhiker in Florida, was scheduled to die that night, and he was fighting to the end," Estrich wrote. "Years later, I talked about that night with Justice Stevens. He had lost faith in the fairness of the death penalty, because no one paid the kind of attention that he had, and Justice Stewart had, and Justice Marshall had, that night long ago. When I asked him why he had changed, he told me that on this, as on so many questions, he had not changed at all. The court had."</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
        <li class="clearfix" style="padding-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 1px #e3e3e3 solid;">
        
            <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=220"><img src="/portal/directory/photos100x100/Hadfield_G2010.jpg" width="100" height="100" alt="Gillian Hadfield" class="fleft" /></a>
        
            <div class="descr">
                <h2><a href="www.dailyjournal.com" target="_blank" style="text-decoration: none;">Los Angeles Daily Journal</a></h2>
                <h3>April 9, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=220">Gillian Hadfield</a></strong></p>
                <p>Prof. Gillian Hadfield was interviewed about the dismal job outlook for law students graduating this year and those who graduated in 2009. Hadfield said law firms are responding to a push back from clients who do not see the value of using first- and second-year associates on their matters. And, she said, law schools need to examine how to produce attorneys who are valuable to clients. "What a lot of firms are facing is real structural changes going on in the market," Hadfield said. "A lot of large corporate clients are pushing back on a lot of things. This is... about the pressure to reduce costs, improve efficiency, increase value."</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
