                <h2 style="color: #000000;">The National Law Journal</h2>
                <h3>March 31, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: USC Gould School of Law</strong></p>
                <p>It was reported that USC Law will launch an international human rights clinic, which will allow students to work on cases before international tribunals in civil litigation involving human rights violations abroad. "It will give students an opportunity to interact with legal regimes outside the United States," said Dean Robert Rasmussen. "Once we get this up and running, it'll give students an opportunity to do some international negotiations, some litigation -- a whole broad variety of competencies that I think we'll expect of lawyers in the 21st century." The clinic will be run by new hire Hannah Garry from University of Colorado School of Law, the story stated. The Recorder also covered the news.</p>
