            <div class="descr">
                <h2 style="color: #000000;">Daily Journal</h2>
                <h3>January 9, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=23758">Robert K. Rasmussen</a></strong></p>
                <p>Dean Robert Rasmussen was quoted about the prospect of Comcast Corp. losing its equity in MGM, which has $3.7 billion in debt. An auction of MGM's assets would raise $2.5 billion at most, far below the studio's debt load, the story stated. In the event of a sale, Comcast and other equity investors could end up with nothing, Rasmussen said. "If it's an auction, equity gets paid back last," he said, adding that an out-of-court workout could be slightly more advantageous to equity holders.</p>
            </div>
