            <img src="/portal/directory/photos100x100/USCLawLogo.gif" width="100" height="100" alt="USC Gould School of Law" class="fleft" />
        
            <div class="descr">
                <h2 style="color: #000000;">Scientific American</h2>
                <h3>January 8, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=300">Elyn Saks</a></strong></p>
                <p>Prof. Elyn Saks was profiled in a Q&A. The story noted that Saks is a Marshall scholar, the recipient of a John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation "genius" grant, and the author of the book "The Center Cannot Hold," about her struggles with schizophrenia. "Even when I am feeling symptoms, when I am working they usually recede -- they become sideline rather than front-and-center. Work focuses my mind and provides a sense of self-esteem," Saks said. "On the other hand, some parts of my job are stressful -- e.g., classroom teaching. I am fortunate to work at a law school willing to accommodate me around teaching. Also traveling and giving talks is stressful for me ... . That's the main reason I have largely stopped accepting invitations to speak. For the most part, though, my job involves thinking and writing, and those, for me, are enormously gratifying."</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
        <li class="clearfix" style="padding-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 1px #e3e3e3 solid;">
        
            <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=211"><img src="/portal/directory/photos100x100/sestrich.jpg" width="100" height="100" alt="Susan Estrich" class="fleft" /></a>
        
            <div class="descr">
                <h2 style="color: #000000;">Ashland Daily Tidings</h2>
                <h3>January 7, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=211">Susan Estrich</a></strong></p>
                <p>Prof. Susan Estrich wrote an op-ed about the efficacy of the U.S. security screening system in the wake of the Christmas Day terrorist attempt. Estrich described her recent experience at an airport, where an elderly woman held up the security line while trying to unfasten the clasp of her bracelet. "The frightening part of the latest directive adding to the list of those warranting special scrutiny individuals who either are from or have been traveling in countries known to harbor terrorists is not that it unfairly profiles, but that we haven't been doing that kind of screening up to this point," Estrich wrote. "We can do everything reasonable to provide the security and stability that may reduce the attractions of radical ideology. But where it has already taken root, our only option is to root it out and destroy the threat. We will not do so successfully if we're all wasting our time fidgeting with the clasp of an antique gold bracelet."</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
        <li class="clearfix" style="padding-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 1px #e3e3e3 solid;">
        
            <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=68021"><img src="/portal/directory/photos100x100/Lonergan_Rebecca_09_176x250.jpg" width="100" height="100" alt="Rebecca Lonergan" class="fleft" /></a>
        
            <div class="descr">
                <h2 style="color: #000000;">St. Petersburg Times</h2>
                <h3>January 5, 2010</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=68021">Rebecca Lonergan</a></strong></p>
                <p>Prof. Rebecca Lonergan was quoted about federal prosecutors finding some of the perpetrators of the mortgage fraud that led to a deluge of U.S. foreclosures. Lonergan said that even though the U.S. Department of Justice has made mortgage fraud a priority, it won't be easy playing catch-up on a long-neglected type of crime. "If they haven't been focusing on mortgage fraud, they won't know who the real actors are," Lonergan said. "So when they want to make a point all of a sudden with a sweep, they won't get big cases. You don't get those unless investigators have been paying attention for a while."</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
        <li class="clearfix" style="padding-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 1px #e3e3e3 solid;">
        
            <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=211"><img src="/portal/directory/photos100x100/sestrich.jpg" width="100" height="100" alt="Susan Estrich" class="fleft" /></a>
        
            <div class="descr">
                <h2 style="color: #000000;">Ashland Daily Tidings</h2>
                <h3>December 30, 2009</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=211">Susan Estrich</a></strong></p>
                <p>Prof. Susan Estrich wrote an op-ed about flying on airplanes in an age of terrorism. "The problem with terror threats is not so much that they force us to live differently. I'd be almost happy to live differently, if it would make a difference," Estrich wrote. "No, it's the inability to do much of anything -- other than get to the airport early and be patient in line -- that makes living with the threat of terror so frightening. For those of us who crave control, crave the sense that we can make things better by doing something, nothing is harder than doing nothing." The Dallas Morning News also cited the op-ed.</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
