            <div class="descr">
                <h2 style="color: #000000;">People</h2>
                <h3>December 19, 2009</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=102">Scott Altman</a></strong></p>
                <p>Vice Dean Scott Altman was cited about the possibilities should golfer Tiger Woods and his wife divorce. Prenups can be challenged, but usually the vulnerability of a prenup will be procedural, such as whether the wife didnt have reasonably good information when she signed it, Altman said. Also, its unlikely that Woods recent admission of infidelity would violate the agreement, unless the prenup says infidelity would set aside some of its terms, Altman added.</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
        <li class="clearfix" style="padding-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 1px #e3e3e3 solid;">
        
            <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=102"><img src="/portal/directory/photos100x100/Altman_S.jpg" width="100" height="100" alt="Scott Altman" class="fleft" /></a>
        
            <div class="descr">
                <h2 style="color: #000000;">Los Angeles Times</h2>
                <h3>December 18, 2009</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=102">Scott Altman</a></strong></p>
                <p>Vice Dean Scott Altman was quoted about the possibilities should golfer Tiger Woods and his wife divorce. "Prenups can be challenged, but usually the vulnerability of a prenup will be procedural, such as whether the wife didn't have reasonably good information when she signed it," Altman said. "That seems unlikely." It's also unlikely that Woods' recent admission of infidelity would violate the agreement, he said. "Not unless the prenup says infidelity would set aside some of its terms," Altman added. Altmans comments were featured in separate stories in People Magazine.</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
