            <div class="descr">
                <h2 style="color: #000000;">The Wall Street Journal</h2>
                <h3>December 15, 2009</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=236">John Matsusaka</a></strong></p>
                <p>Prof. John Matsusaka was quoted regarding a rift between backers of same-sex marriage about when the issue should next be placed on the California ballot. Matsusaka said that returning to the ballot repeatedly can be risky. "We've seen this happen with other issues, where they put them in sequential elections, and they just keep trying and getting rejected," Matsusaka said, citing a California abortion-related parental notification initiative that has failed three times in four years. "Once the voters make up their minds on an issue, they feel irked if people prod them again." The story also cited the University of Southern California College of Letters, Arts and Sciences/Los Angeles Times Poll, which showed that 60 percent of voters do not want to see the gay marriage issue back on the ballot in November.</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
