                <h2 style="color: #000000;">Pasadena Star-News</h2>
                <h3>November 21, 2009</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=230">Martin Levine</a></strong></p>
                <p>Prof. Martin Levine was quoted in an article about William Cottrell, who was diagnosed with Asperger's syndrome during his 2004 trial for conspiracy in the vandalizing and firebombing of more than 130 vehicles. A judge ruled that Asperger's could not be introduced at the trial; an appeals court later ruled that the decision was a mistake and tossed out Cottrell's arson convictions, leaving just the conspiracy conviction. Levine said it would have made little sense for the government to retry Cottrell, since he faced the same sentence on the conspiracy count anyway. "The prosecutor has very little reason to spend the time and resources on having a re-trial," Levine said.</p>
            </div>
