        <li class="clearfix" style="padding-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 1px #e3e3e3 solid;">
        
            <img src="/portal/directory/photos100x100/USCLawLogo.gif" width="100" height="100" alt="USC Gould School of Law" class="fleft" />
        
            <div class="descr">
                <h2 style="color: #000000;">Tax Notes</h2>
                <h3>November 16, 2009</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: USC Gould School of Law</strong></p>
                <p>Dean Robert Rasmussen and three USC professors were quoted in a story about USC Laws new Master of Laws in Taxation program. Our goal, quite simply, is to offer the best tax education possible, Rasmussen said. Like most LLM programs, the focus is on preparing students for tax practice. But for those students interested in theory, there will be ample opportunity to take theoretical courses as well, Prof. Thomas Griffith said. The way were approaching the tax LLM program is that the JD program is an extremely important foundation in critical thinking and in exposure to both doctrine and trends in academic thought, but is not itself tantamount to preparation for being a successful tax practitioner the day one finishes law school, Prof. Edward Kleinbard said. To me, tax is too important to leave to the people who understand it. Knowing the basics of tax, and ideally some of the options for its future, is part of being a citizen. Prof. Edward McCaffery said.</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        
    
        
