                <h3>October 20, 2009</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=211">Susan Estrich</a></strong></p>
                <p>Prof. Susan Estrich wrote an op-ed about Carol Greider, who was recently awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine. "Greider was a 23-year-old graduate student at Berkeley when, on Christmas Day in 1984, she made the discovery that led to this prize. She was working for a woman who had been trained by a man who believed in supporting women. This is not really complicated," Estrich wrote. "Women succeed the same way men do. Someone gives them a chance. One of the most depressing trends I have encountered of late is women my age, women in their 40s, 50s and 60s, who are unwilling to help the younger women coming into our professions, resentful that it is easier for them than it was for us, dismissive of their desires to balance work and life with greater freedom than we had."</p>
