                <h2 style="color: #000000;">National Public Radio</h2>
                <h3>October 2, 2009</h3>
                <p><strong>Re: <a href="/faculty/contactinfo.cfm?detailid=211">Susan Estrich</a></strong></p>
                <p>Prof. Susan Estrich was interviewed on All Things Considered about filmmaker Roman Polanski, who was recently arrested in Switzerland, 30 years after he fled the United States to avoid sentencing for a 1977 statutory rape conviction. Estrich spoke about her own experience as a rape victim. "My heart goes out to this woman and her desire to make this all go away," Estrich said. "As a matter of fact, most of us who've been raped in one way or another want to close our eyes and make it go away. But rape isn't a crime against the victim. It's a crime against the state. To be a fugitive from justice is as serious a crime as the underlying rape offense."</p>
